ing to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Umfraville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Umfreville (La Manche) or Offranville (Seine-Maritime)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Umfraville VII was born about 1220, in Castle Ward, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Umfreville, was 30 and his mother, Mrs. Eva De Umfreville, was 74. He had at least 2 daughters."},"et":{"about 1220–":"umbes 1220–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1249–Female":"1249–Surnud","1259–Female":"1259–Surnud","1192–1244":"1192–1244","1148–Female":"1148–Surnud","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1148":"1148","1244":"1244","1220":"1220","about 1212":"umbes 1212","about 1220":"umbes 1220","1192":"1192","Birtley, Northumberland, England":"Birtley, Northumberland, England","Kirkley, Castle Ward, Northumberland, England":"Cas